DAG & variable coding

M. Rolland

21/01/2021

Intro

Here we present the final DAG for the babylab analysis and decide which covariates will be used in the final models. Then we decide on the appropriate coding. And finally we select variables according to p-value (<0.2) to present the final model.

We used a mixed effect model as discussed in the model_validation.html document with fixation duration as the outcome.

DAG

Produced by M. Rolland and C. Philippat version of 27/11/2020:

According to the DAG the analysis confounders are:

  • Ethnicity
  • Maternal age at conception
  • Exposure to other contaminant (tobacco)
  • Maternal depression
  • Parental education
  • Parity

In addition to these covariates we add experiment hour which is suspected to be a strong predictor of the outcome (see data_exploration.html). Other outcome predictors (in blue on the DAG) are not considered as they are poorly measured in Sepages with many NAs. Child age is colinear with age at assessment so cannot be included in the mixed effect model.

Child sex will also be added. WHY?

Gestational age and birthweight are on the pathway so wont be included in the main analysis, but will be added in the sensitivity analyses.

Choice of tobacco indicator

Only for tobacco the choice of the indicator to use is not straight forward as we have several types of indicator (contiunous, binary) at different periods of time (whole pregnancy, T1, T2, etc).

Given the low number of smokers in sepages, we will not consider the continuous variables or the binary indicators for high consumption, we will only consider the binary indicators indicating whether the participant smoked/did not smoke in a given time frame.

Tobacco indicators:

var label n_na smoking
mo_tob_grstt1_yn Maternal smoking between preg. conception and detection, N/Y 8 21 / 180
mo_tob_grt1_yn Maternal smoking during 1st trim of pregnancy, after diagnosis, N/Y 8 7 / 180
mo_tob_grt2_yn Maternal smoking during 2nd trim of pregnancy, N/Y 5 6 / 183
mo_tob_grt3_yn Maternal smoking during 3rd trim of pregnancy, N/Y 16 4 / 172
mo_tob_gr_anyt_yn Maternal smoking during any trim of diagnosed pregnancy, N/Y 12 10 / 176
mo_tob_granyt_yn_recalc NA 7 24 / 181
  • very few smokers at T3
  • many missing for T3 and the any time during pregnancy (after detection) variables
    • will not consider smoking at T3 and any time during pregnancy after detection (instead we will consider any time during pregnancy including between conception and detection)

Tobacco model with different tobacco vars adjusted on the other covars limited to data with no missing for smoking pre detection, at T1, at T2 and any time since conception ordered by decreasing beta (including recalculated smoked any time after conception yes/no):

var Coefficient CI_low CI_high p
mo_tob_granyt_yn_recalc 14.421803 -9.604816 38.44842 0.2394135
mo_tob_grstt1_yn 14.421803 -9.604816 38.44842 0.2394135
mo_tob_grt1_yn 1.306971 -44.205552 46.81949 0.9551157
mo_tob_grt2_yn -3.822231 -54.897144 47.25268 0.8833882
  • highest beta for smoking pre-detection and any time
  • we will favor smoked any time (easier to interpret)

Experiment hour

We have seen that there seems to be a non linear relationship between experiment hour and some of the scores (see data_exploration.html).

Conclusion

Final suggested model covariates and coding after selecting for p < 0.2:

  • Maternal age as continuous
  • Tobacco as smoked yes/no any time after conception
  • Experiment hour as natural spline with 4 DF

Annex

Coding reminder

  • mo_edu
    • 1 Primaire
    • 2 College
    • 3 BEP
    • 4 CAP
    • 5 Lycee
    • 6 Bac +2
    • 7 Bac +3-4
    • 8 >=Bac +5
  • parity
    • 0 First child
    • 1 Second child
    • 2 Third child or more
